HWPUA was synthesized by using stearyl methacrylate and 2,2,3,4,4,4-hexafluorobutyl methacrylate as low surface energy compounds (Fig. 4
                        ). The chemical structure of HWPUA was characterized by 1H NMR and FT-IR. As shown in Fig. 5
                        a, the 1H NMR characteristic peaks at 1.31, 2.35, 3.06, 4.32, and 5.40 ppm were attributed to −NHCOO−, −CH2COO−, −CH2OCO−, −CH2−CF2−, and −CHF−, respectively. The FT-IR spectrum of HWPUA displays the CO stretching, NH bending, and C-N stretching vibrations at 1723, 1533, and 1460 cm−1, respectively. These results confirm the successful synthesis of HWPUA. The band at 424 cm−1 was attributed to the Si-O-Si bending vibration, which indicated the formation of HWPUA/DFNS@CQDs-MoS2 composite. The mechanical properties of HWPUA and HWPUA/DFNS@CQDs-MoS2 membranes were measured by tensile tests. The strain–stress curves are displayed in Fig. 5b. The tensile strength values of HWPUA and HWPUA/DFNS@CQDs-MoS2 were 18.4 and 13.3 MPa, respectively. Compared to pure HWPUA, the elongation at break of HWPUA/DFNS@CQDs-MoS2 decreased from 170.5% to 150.2%. This phenomenon could be the result of the limited polymer segment motion due to the filler [45]. The water contact angle increased from 101° to 108°, which can be explained by the construction of the micro-nano structure caused by DFNS@CQDs-MoS2 nanoparticles (Fig. 5b inset) [46]. As shown in Fig S5, the surface of the HWPUA membrane was smooth and flat, while the surface of HWPUA/DFNS@CQDs-MoS2 showed a rough structure. The photoluminescence (PL) properties of the HWPUA/DFNS@CQDs-MoS2 membrane are illustrated in Fig. S6. The HWPUA/DFNS@CQDs-MoS2 membrane exhibited an emission peak at 452 nm under excitation wavelength of 465 nm. The emulsion was drawn as ink on the filter paper, which showed a gray mark under ambient light and blue fluorescence under UV irradiation at 365 nm (Fig. S6 inset) [47].

The antibacterial performance of uncoated leather, HWPUA coated leather, and HWPUA/DFNS@CQDs-MoS2 coated leather was assessed by determining the zone of inhibition. As shown in Fig. 8
                        , the HWPUA coated leather showed a low antibacterial performance, which was probably due to the anti-adhesive properties of the hydrophobic surface. After the addition of DFNS@CQDs-MoS2 into HWPUA coating, the inhibition zone diameter of S. aureus, E. coli, and A. niger was significantly larger due to the anti-adhesive and bactericidal effects. To further explore the morphology of anti-adhesive and antibacterial surfaces after treating the bacteria with the leather samples, SEM was used to analyze the leather surfaces before and after HWPUA and HWPUA/DFNS@CQDs-MoS2 coating (Fig. 9
                        ). The uncoated leather showed a large number of S. aureus, E. coli, and A.niger cells which grew and formed biofilms on the surfaces. After coating with HWPUA, the surface contained some S. aureus and E. coli cells, but no A. niger cells. Significant changes were observed for the leather coated with HWPUA/DFNS@CQDs-MoS2. The hydrophobic surface hindered the initial adhesion of bacteria, but a few bacterial cells still grew on the surfaces. The addition of an antibacterial agent can completely hinder adhesion and kill the adhered bacteria [15,51].
